    <h1>The Art and Power of Gymnastics</h1>
    <h2>
        What is Gymnastics?
    </h2>
    <p>Gymnastics is a breathtaking sport that requires a unique combination of strength, flexibility, balance, agility, and immense dedication. It is not just about physical power; it's about executing complex movements with perfect control and artistic grace. Gymnasts spend years perfecting routines that often last just a little over a minute.</p>
    <h2>    How the Gymnastics World Works:</h2>
    <p>The world of competitive gymnastics is highly structured. At the top level, you have the Olympic Games and the World Championships.
But how do they win? It's all about the Code of Points. Gone are the days of the "Perfect 10."</p>
     <p> Curious to see the rules in action or find a local club?  <a href="https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/rules/" target="_blank">Visit the official website of the International Gymnastics Federation for more details.</a> </p>
     <hr />  
    <h2>Today, a gymnast's final score is made up of two parts:</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <h4>Difficulty Score (D-Score):</h4> <p>Points given for the hardest elements in the routine. There is no maximum limit!</p>
        </li>
       
          <li>
<h4>Execution Score (E-Score):</h4> <p>Starts at 10.0, and the judges deduct points for every mistake (like bent knees, taking a step on the landing, or falling).</p>
          </li>
    </ul>
     <hr />  
    <h2>Men vs. Women: What's the Difference?</h2>
    <p>While both men and women need incredible strength and flexibility, they compete on different apparatuses designed to highlight different physical attributes.</p>
    <ul>  
        <li> <h4>Men's Artistic Gymnastics (MAG): </h4>   <p>Men compete on six apparatuses: The Floor Exercise, Pommel Horse, Still Rings, Vault, Parallel Bars, and Horizontal (High) Bar. Men's routines do not use music and are heavily focused on demonstrating extreme upper-body strength and explosive power. </p></li>

           <li> <h4> Women's Artistic Gymnastics (WAG):</h4>   <p> Women compete on four apparatuses: The Vault, Uneven Bars, Balance Beam, and Floor Exercise. Their routines, especially on the floor, often incorporate music and dance elements, focusing on a mix of acrobatics and artistic expression.</p></li>
    </ul>
